<div id="review_73753570" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/73753570" />
    <a title="Candace" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/1629175-candace"><img alt="Candace" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1612926007p2/1629175.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/73753570?book_show_action=true">Oct 07, 2009</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Candace" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Candace" href="/user/show/1629175-candace">Candace</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer73753570" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer6551699709863205192">This is quite the novel, as full and satisfying as anything I&apos;ve read in some time. Its picture of Mexico in the 30&apos;s is spot on, and the characters of Diego Rivera, Frida Kahlo, and Lev Trotsky feel fresh and sharp. <br/><br/>The political correctness which bored me in Barbara Kingsolver&apos;s novels seem naive has developed--she&apos;s showing, not preaching. A wonderful read by an author who is at her best.</span>
  <span id="freeText6551699709863205192" style="display:none">This is quite the novel, as full and satisfying as anything I've read in some time. Its picture of Mexico in the 30's is spot on, and the characters of Diego Rivera, Frida Kahlo, and Lev Trotsky feel fresh and sharp. <br /><br />The political correctness which bored me in Barbara Kingsolver's novels seem naive has developed--she's showing, not preaching. A wonderful read by an author who is at her best.</span>
  <a data-text-id="6551699709863205192" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
